						<div class="postbody">Well, maybe to put this in perspective, I'm thinking about my DVD collection.  All of my DVDs are in a box in the basement.  The content, along with cover art, actor info, studio info, etc. is saved on a computer and played from there (think of each DVD directory as a rom file).  My DVD player (i.e., emulator) reads all of the DVD info and I can view cover art, sort by release date, director, etc.  I own the DVD (not pirated), but I still appreciate having all of the details easily accessible.
<br />
<br />Now, this could all be stored in a separate database, but why not keep it with the game itself in a single file?  Seems less complicated.
<br />
<br />With the ubiquity of broadband and giant hard drives, additional file size should not be an issue.  Although, again, if the header is flexible enough, feel free to strip out anything you don't want without worry.</div>

					
